ChatGPT said:
No, there is no â€œadd onlyâ€ or â€œappendâ€ option for KMS key policies using Terraform.

Hereâ€™s why:
AWS KMS key policies are single documents.
Each key has one policy, which is a JSON document containing all permissions.

Terraformâ€™s aws_kms_key_policy always manages the entire document.
When you apply, it will overwrite the keyâ€™s policy with whatever is defined in your Terraform code.

There is no way to â€œjust addâ€ a role/statement using Terraformâ€™s aws_kms_key_policy resourceâ€”you must provide the full, merged policy.

Why canâ€™t you just add a new role with Terraform?
If you use only the new statement (for the new role), all old statements will be removed from the policy.

If you use both old + new statements in your code, both permissions are present (thatâ€™s the right way).

Is there any workaround?
No official Terraform workaround exists to â€œaddâ€ or â€œappendâ€ a role without restating the entire policy.

If you need a one-time update and donâ€™t want Terraform to manage the policy, you can add a new statement manually in the AWS Console or via the AWS CLI.

But, once you let Terraform manage the policy, you must keep all desired statements in your Terraform code.

Summary Table
Method	What happens
AWS Console / CLI	You can add/append new statements as you like
Terraform	You must manage the full policy (old + new)

Bottom line:
Terraform = full policy only (old and new merged together).

No append/partial update possible.

If you want, share your current KMS policy and the ARN of the new role you want to add.
I will merge them and give you a ready-to-use Terraform script.











